{"id":"2105.09884","submitter":"Nicola Bastianello","authors":"Nicola Bastianello, Liam Madden, Ruggero Carli, Emiliano Dall'Anese","title":"A Stochastic Operator Framework for Static and Online Optimization with\n  Sub-Weibull Errors","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC cs.SY eess.SY","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This paper proposes a stochastic operator framework to analyze the\nconvergence of iterative algorithms for both static and online optimization\nwith: (i) stochastic errors in the algorithmic steps, and (ii) random\ncoordinate updates. To this end, the paper focuses on operators of the form $\\T\n\\x = (\\T_1 \\x, \\ldots, \\T_n \\x)$, defined over the direct sum of possibly\ninfinite-dimensional Hilbert spaces, and investigates the convergence of the\nassociated stochastic Banach-Picard iteration. Results in terms of convergence\nin mean and in high-probability are presented when the errors affecting the\noperator follow a sub-Weibull distribution, and when updates $\\T_i \\x$ are\nperformed based on a Bernoulli random variable. In particular, the results are\nderived for the cases where $\\T$ is component-wise contractive and averaged,\nwith results in terms of convergence to the unique fixed point and cumulative\nfixed-point residual, respectively. Links with exiting results in terms of\nalmost sure convergence are provided. In the online optimization context, the\noperator changes at each iteration to reflect changes in the underlying\noptimization problem. This leads to an online Banach-Picard iteration, and\nsimilar results are derived where the bounds for the convergence in mean and\nhigh-probability further depend on the evolution of fixed points (\\emph{i.e.},\noptimal solutions of the time-varying optimization problem).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 20 May 2021 16:30:11 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 12 Aug 2022 16:25:00 GMT"}